Cp. ἓ 18, squalore huius et sordibus laetatur: Becker’s Gallus, sc. viii. (Chresimus to Gallus), ‘ hear the counsel of a faithful servant. Divest yourself of all the insignia of the distinction befitting your rank. Throw carelessly round you the worst and oldest toga you can find, and publicly display the sorrow with which the interdict has filled you.' ‘H0w,’ retorted Gallus, ‘ humble myself and go about in dirty garments like a criminal, and beg for mercy !' Such was the mourning adopted at Rome, whether in times of bereavement or of peril from a heavy accusation: the sufferet assumed the sordida vestis (vestem mutavit), let his hair grow, and discarded all decorations.
